Where `imageCacheItem` retains data like `{format: ..., flipY: ..., image: ...}`.

I couldn't think of a way to obtain a key from `texture.image` without modifying the element itself (`image.src` is not necessarily safe; it could be a `<canvas/>`). One alternative to the array of configs would be a separate map of IDs I suppose:

```
imageElementKeys = new Map();
if ( !imageElementKeys.has( image ) ) {
  imageElementKeys.set( image, s.size );
}
var imageKey = imageElementKeys.get( image ) + ':' + texture.flipY + ':' + texture.format;
if ( ! imageCache.has( imageKey ) {
  // ...
}
```

I'm fine with changing the signature of `processImage()`.

@donmccurdy @takahirox 

I've had a good read around and since Map() only supports reference-types for keys (I'm a C++ dev btw so this is all quite new to me) there doesn't appear to be a way to use a compound key without adding a lot of complexity or using an external library (such as blockhash-js, crypto-js etc). I did come across a couple of forums discussing ES7 value-type implementation for Map() mentioned here: https://esdiscuss.org/topic/value-types-as-map-keys-in-es7 but I've searched all over the place and can't find very much else on it.

So I think for this upcoming milestone, it comes down to a choice between one of your two Map() ideas or an alternative Array implementation:

```
cachedData.images = []
...
function processImage( image, mimeType, flipY ) {
	var result = cachedData.images.find( function( entry ) {
		return 	entry.img === image &&
				entry.mimeType === mimeType &&
				entry.flipY === flipY;
	});

	if( result != undefined ) {
		return result.index;
	}
...
	var entry = {
		img: image,
		mimeType: mimeType,
		flipY: flipY,
		index: outputJSON.images.length - 1
	}
	cachedData.images.push( entry );
	return entry.index;
}
```

O(n) worst case for the array versus ~O(log n) worst case for the maps. The advantage of the array is that it's simple (just the one datastructure to navigate). Sorry it's taken me so long, happy to go with whatever you guys decide anyway :-)

